        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Local authority</strong> is the degree to which Google and other search engines perceive a business as the trusted, relevant expert within a specific geographic area. It determines Local Pack rankings, "near me" search visibility, and whether Google chooses your business over a competitor with a larger website but weaker local presence.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Ranking impact</div>
            <div class="tms-value">High — all three local factors</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Build time</div>
            <div class="tms-value">3-6 months (early signals: 4-8 wks)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">A national brand with a 60 domain authority can lose Local Pack rankings to a two-year-old plumbing business with 120 Google reviews, consistent citations, and four neighbourhood-level landing pages. That's local authority at work — and it's entirely buildable if you know which signals matter.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is local authority?</h2>
        <p>Local authority is not a single metric or score — it's Google's aggregated signal of how trustworthy, relevant, and prominent a business is within a defined geographic area. Google evaluates local authority across three dimensions it openly acknowledges as local ranking factors:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Relevance</strong> — how closely your business matches what the searcher is looking for (GBP category, services listed, keywords on your site)</li>
          <li><strong>Distance</strong> — how far your business is from the searcher or the searched location</li>
          <li><strong>Prominence</strong> — how well-known and trusted your business is both online and offline (reviews, citations, backlinks, brand mentions)</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Prominence is where local authority lives. Distance is fixed. Relevance is table stakes. The businesses that consistently outrank competitors in the Local Pack do so by building prominence signals that tell Google: "This business is the trusted local expert for this service category."</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Google's confirmation</div>
          <p>Google's local search documentation explicitly states: "Prominence refers to how well known a business is. Some places are more prominent in the offline world, and search results try to reflect this in local ranking... Google review count and review score factor into local search ranking."</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why local authority matters for rankings</h2>
        <p>Local authority is the differentiator when distance and relevance are equal across competing businesses. In most local markets, every plumber or dentist within a 2-mile radius has roughly the same distance to any given searcher. Relevance is similar — they all list the same services. The tiebreaker is authority. Five reasons it drives outcomes:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Local Pack placement.</strong> The 3-listing box (formerly Map Pack) in Google Search is directly driven by GBP optimisation, review velocity, and citation consistency — all local authority signals. Getting into it can generate 3-5x more phone calls than ranking on page one organically.</li>
          <li><strong>Near-me search dominance.</strong> "Near me" and implicit-location searches trigger location-based ranking. Local authority determines which businesses surface when a searcher 0.3 miles away types "emergency plumber."</li>
          <li><strong>Knowledge Panel trust.</strong> A business with high local authority gets a richer Knowledge Panel — star rating, review count, popular times, Q&amp;A — that converts searchers before they even visit the site.</li>
          <li><strong>Compounding effect.</strong> More reviews lead to higher rankings, which lead to more clicks, which generate more reviews. Local authority builds on itself over time in ways paid ads cannot replicate.</li>
          <li><strong>AI search citation.</strong> As ChatGPT and Gemini answer location queries, they draw on business data from Google's local knowledge graph. Higher local authority means your business appears in AI-generated local recommendations.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How Google measures local authority</h2>
        <p>Google aggregates dozens of signals to assess local authority. The core input categories, in order of impact:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Google Business Profile completeness.</strong> Primary category, secondary categories, services, products, Q&amp;A, attributes, photos (minimum 10), posts frequency. An incomplete GBP signals low investment in local presence.</li>
          <li><strong>Review quantity and velocity.</strong> Not just star rating — total review count, review freshness, and the rate at which new reviews arrive all feed the prominence calculation. A restaurant with 340 reviews outranks one with 30, assuming similar recency.</li>
          <li><strong>Review quality and response rate.</strong> Google's systems read review text for service mentions and sentiment. Responding to reviews within 24 hours is a positive engagement signal.</li>
          <li><strong>Citation consistency.</strong> NAP (Name, Address, Phone) accuracy across directories — Yelp, Apple Maps, Bing Places, data aggregators — tells Google this business is stable and real. Inconsistent citations (different phone numbers, misspelled addresses) erode trust.</li>
          <li><strong>Local backlinks.</strong> Links from local newspapers, chambers of commerce, neighbourhood blogs, and city-specific directories carry more local authority weight than generic national links.</li>
          <li><strong>On-site local signals.</strong> LocalBusiness schema markup, city and neighbourhood mentions in page copy, service-area pages with local keywords, and geo-tagged images all tell Google what area you serve.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="types">Local authority vs domain authority — key differences</h2>

