        <h2 id="examples">Real local authority examples</h2>
        <p>Here is how local authority plays out in practice across three business scenarios.</p>

        <h3>1. Denver plumber — from invisible to dominant</h3>
        <p>A Denver plumbing company started with 12 Google reviews and no citation profile. Over 6 months they: built 80+ directory citations with consistent NAP, reached 140 Google reviews (4.8 average), published monthly GBP posts, and added four neighbourhood landing pages (Capitol Hill, Cherry Creek, Highlands, Stapleton). Result: top-3 Local Pack for "emergency plumber Denver" and 3-5 calls per week from Google alone, up from near zero.</p>

        <h3>2. Multi-location restaurant chain — scaling local authority</h3>
        <p>A 12-location restaurant chain with inconsistent GBP data (wrong hours, outdated photos, zero posts) ran a 90-day local authority project: standardised all GBP listings, ran a review velocity campaign, and published weekly posts. GBP impressions increased 60% in Q1. Average position in Local Finder improved from 4.2 to 2.1 across locations.</p>

        <h3>3. New salon vs established competitor</h3>
        <p>A new salon opened near an established competitor with 280 reviews. By the end of month 4, the new salon had 95 reviews (vs the competitor's 11 in the same period), a fully built citation profile, and LocalBusiness schema on every page. It overtook the competitor for "hair salon [neighbourhood]" despite having half the operating history.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Local authority vs local SEO — what's the difference?</h2>
        <p>Local authority is a component of local SEO — specifically the prominence dimension. Local SEO is the full discipline. You can think of it as:</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Local Authority builds</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Google review count and velocity</li>
              <li>Citation profile breadth and accuracy</li>
              <li>Local backlinks from neighbourhood sites</li>
              <li>GBP completeness and engagement</li>
              <li>Brand mentions in local press</li>
            </ul>
