            <ul>
              <li>Keyword research for local queries</li>
              <li>On-page optimisation and schema</li>
              <li>Location page content strategy</li>
              <li>Technical site health</li>
              <li>Tracking Local Pack rank weekly</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 best practices for building local authority</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Complete your Google Business Profile to 100%.</strong> Fill every field: primary category, secondary categories, attributes, services with descriptions, products with pricing, business description (750 chars), at least 10 photos, and Q&amp;A populated with your own questions and answers.</li>
          <li><strong>Build a review velocity system.</strong> The rate of new reviews matters as much as total count. Set up a post-service review request workflow — SMS or email within 2 hours of job completion achieves 2-4x the review rate of a link buried in an invoice.</li>
          <li><strong>Audit and fix citations across top 50 directories.</strong> Use BrightLocal or Whitespark to find every listing. Fix NAP inconsistencies before building new ones — bad data amplified is worse than no data.</li>
          <li><strong>Earn local backlinks specifically.</strong> Sponsor a local event, join the chamber of commerce (most give a do-follow directory link), contribute data or quotes to local news stories. Five local links from .org or newspaper domains beat 50 generic directory links.</li>
          <li><strong>Publish GBP posts weekly.</strong> Google uses GBP post frequency as a freshness signal. 52 posts per year is the minimum for competitive markets. Tie posts to local events, seasonal services, and FAQ topics.</li>
          <li><strong>Build neighbourhood-level landing pages.</strong> If you serve five suburbs, create a unique page for each with: 500+ words of original content, local schema, and embedded Google Map. Thin location pages with identical content trigger duplicate-content penalties.</li>
          <li><strong>Respond to every review within 24 hours.</strong> Google's local ranking documentation cites engagement as a signal. Responding to negative reviews professionally converts fence-sitters into customers and signals active business management.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — buying citations in bulk</div>
          <p>Citation aggregator services that blast your NAP to 500 directories in 48 hours routinely create inconsistencies — slightly different business names, wrong phone extensions, misformatted addresses. Google detects inconsistency across the citation web and reduces your prominence score. Build citations methodically across verified sources, starting with the top 20 by authority.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common local authority mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Keyword-stuffing your business name on GBP.</strong> Adding "Denver | Emergency Plumber" to your business name violates Google's guidelines and risks suspension.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring negative reviews.</strong> An unanswered negative review is a conversion killer. It also signals to Google that you're not actively managing your presence.</li>
          <li><strong>Using the same boilerplate copy on every location page.</strong> Google treats near-identical location pages as thin content and may not rank any of them.</li>
          <li><strong>Letting GBP data go stale.</strong> Wrong holiday hours, outdated phone numbers, or a closed secondary location left live will tank your local authority score and generate customer complaints.</li>
          <li><strong>Conflating domain authority with local authority.</strong> A DA 70 site is not automatically locally authoritative. Separate link-building work from local authority work — they need different tactics.</li>
        </ul>

